It’s #Veganuary! I applaud anyone who is trying out a plant-based diet this month, and I want you to set yourself up for success, so I’ll be sharing tips and info about key things that lead to a lifestyle change you can sustain long term!

This is by far one of the most basic and key components to long term success: balanced meals!

Like with any diet, plant-based or not, it’s important to incorporate enough hunger-satiating foods like proteins, fats, and starchy carbs.

This recipe is sesame udon noodles with seitan sausages, topped with cucumber and green onion curls. Udon noodles are my starchy carbs, roasted sesame paste provides fat and iron, while seitan provides protein. And we can’t forget veggies, so cucumber and green onion add fibre, vitamins, and delicious crunchy texture. The full recipe and measurements are on TheVietVegan.com

I strive to share plant-based recipes and vegan lifestyle content to show you all the possibilities of a vegan lifestyle, while acknowledging the barriers and difficulties. I hope to help you navigate those challenges so you can maintain this lifestyle as long as possible!

Got questions? Let me know in the comments and I’ll do my best to answer in the comments or a reel!

#thevietvegan #plantbased #vegan #veganfood

A salty rant from my stories turned into a reel because I think this is really important information for people new to a plant-based diet AND for people who are promoting a plant-based diet.

We are not helping anyone if we promote misinformation about certain foods being high protein when they are not. LEAVE BROCCOLI ALONE! Let those green trees be the delicious sides they were meant to be. Nobody’s digestion and wallet can sustain that much broccoli as a protein source 🥲

#veganuary #vegan #plantbaseddiet #plantbased #whatveganseat #veganfood

Maybe an unpopular opinion but I think the health related motivations for being vegan are the weakest of the typical trio of ethical, health, and environmental benefits of a vegan lifestyle. Plus, some argue that this would make you plant-based if you’re not in it for the social justice of animal rights, and I don’t disagree.

Anecdotally, I find the people who went vegan for health-related reasons are more likely to fall back from an exclusively plant-based diet, citing lack of results, balance, convenience, and/or social pressures as their reasons.

While I of course think that any effort is better than no effort, I can’t help but feel like the exaggerated health claims people bestow upon a vegan lifestyle can be a disappointment when people realize that it isn’t actually a cure-all. Plus, the health benefits are the most apparent in those following a whole-foods plant-based diet, and I personally don’t follow that lifestyle and would find it limiting. We all have different definitions of what is healthful and balanced for our own lifestyles. I’m just trying to be realistic of how I expect the average person eats, even vegan.

My takeaway? Focus on advocating for the environmental and ethical reasons for eating plant-based and leading a vegan lifestyle. Acknowledge that there are health benefits provided people are more strict about a whole-foods plant-based diet, but don’t advertise unattainable health claims that all depend on factors other than one’s diet.

What do you think?

Also as always, the recipe for this vegan lasagna is on TheVietVegan.com

#veganuary #plantbased #plantbaseddiet #vegan

I’ve fully entered a new era where I would rather make food at home instead of eating out and it’s really weird but awesome. I can’t tell if I’m saving money or not though. I probably am but vegan alternatives can be $$

We’ve been doing a lot of meal prep (mostly for Eddie’s work lunches) but also pre-prepping aspects of meals because chasing a toddler around all day is tiring haha. Lately I’ve been prepping banchan for kimbap/bibimbap!

After many requests, a dedicated kimbap recipe post is on my blog, so refer to that if you wanna know how I make this Korean classic!

Unlike sushi, kimbap is made with individually prepared components and rice seasoned with sesame oil and salt. The outside is also coated with some sesame oil, which means it doesn’t stick to each other, has a beautiful glossy sheen and has an extra bit of sesame flavour.

No dipping or extra sauce is required so it’s the perfect portable food. They’re often prepared and then cut into thin coins before wrapping in foil to bring to eat on the go.

I love eating kimbap with kimchi and a vegan shin ramen cup! With a bubbly drink on the side, and this is 😮‍💨😮‍💨😮‍💨

Still deep in my herbalicious phase. I used to just use herbs sparingly, but now I put them in smoothies, chop them up into chimichurri or other herby chutneys, and add them to soups, pasta, or a regular dinner component: cilantro garlic rice!

I also love using herbs to add extra nutrition: leafy green herbs are packed with various antioxidants and vitamins, so not only so they taste amazing and add a lot of freshness, they’re also good for you.

Top tier herbs in our house: cilantro, flat leaf parsley (curly can gtfo honestly), basil, fish mint, sorrel, shiso and dill. I LOVE A DILL. 

Anyway, cilantro garlic rice is an oldie but goodie recipe on the blog. I just wanted to spruce up my feed with an herby photo to portray my current obsession with herbs.

✨It’s my reclaiming oneself era✨

📸: gym selfies, things we spot on Bean’s walks, cold noodles from Artisan Noodle Plus, yuzu citron tart, hangs with friends at @vegtofest ft a dumpster cameo lol, a solo day in Toronto, and the never ending dishes.

My mental health has had lots of ups and downs over the last year or so, and I feel like I’m finally emerging from this weird pause as lockdowns, shifts in friendships, motherhood, and changes to my body as a result of postpartum has been a lot of adjustment.

I’ve been feeling stronger, more energized (but still burnt out at times), more present and more like Lisa. I have been reading, playing video games, cooking, and exercising to claw my way back to the person I was before all the lockdowns and parenthood, while still trying to be a good mom.

September has felt like I hit some huge strides in my strength and physical health recovery, and I have found more direction when it comes to the recipes I want to create.

I was hitting my stride until Bean got sick and had a week of broken sleep so I’ve had to reset, but I have high hopes for October. September always feels like new beginnings even though I haven’t been in school for a long time.

I’m officially making this a series because these Set It & Forget It meals have been clutch for giving me time to do what I need to do and still feed Bean wholesome and tasty meals.

They frequently ask me for “Rice?!” whenever I’m taking too long to cook other meals so they’ve just associated these rice cooker meals with “Hurry up Mom I’m hungry” vibes 😂

Full recipe is on thevietvegan.com, I haven’t tested an Instant Pot or regular rice cooker version yet but if you are one of peeps, I have measurement suggestions on the blog post based on my last rice cooker meal.

I think the next one should be lemon & garlicky? Or maybe tomato rice and beans? What do you think?

Set It & Forget It Ep 2: Butternut Squash Risotto made with @violifeca in the InstantPot. [ad]

Only 10 minutes of active cooking results in this deliciously creamy and cheesy dairy-free butternut squash risotto! I like to serve this with BBQ soy curls (I know, not a common pairing for risotto but it works.)

Makes 4 servings

1 tbsp dairy-free butter
1 onion, finely diced
3 cloves garlic, minced
4 leaves sage, stem removed and finely diced
1 cup (190 g) arborio rice 
1/4 cup apple cider vinegar
3 cups water (or veggie broth)
2 tsp broth paste (omit if using veggie broth)
2 cups diced butternut squash
2/3 cup @Violifeca dairy-free mozza shreds
1/3 cup grated @Violifeca dairy-free parm (about 40 g) + extra for garnish
1/2 of lemon, juiced

Saute onions in dairy-free butter until translucent (about 2 minutes). Then add garlic, and sage, and stir for about 30 sec. Add arborio rice and toast for about a minute or so. Add apple cider vinegar, veggie broth, and diced butternut squash and stir to coat everything. Close the lid and set to sealing, then pressure cook on high for 6 minutes, and let pressure naturally release (about 15 min)

Set pressure cooker back onto Saute, then add Violife dairy-free mozza shreds and grated parm style wedge. Mix in to melt. Add lemon juice and mix in, then serve immediately!
